<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1437,433,854]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,433,458]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Wings oval; FW costal area broad basally, subcostal veinlets closely spaced and mostly shallowly forked in both wings, veinlets simple at wing base and distally; first branch of RP originating near origin of RP on RA; FW RP with 16 branches, HW with 17 branches; both wings with outer gradate series well developed, inner gradate series absent, radial crossveins numerous in basal half of wing, slightly more irregularly arranged in HW; M forked slightly distal to origin of RP1; MA and MP with 2â€“4 branches distally in both wings; CuA and CuP strongly pectinately branched in both wings with shallow end-twigging very close to wing margin, FW with six branches in CuA and nine branches in CuP, HW with seven branches in CuA and 12 branches in CuP; FW A1 with seven pectinate branches, HW A1 with four pectinate branches; FW A2 with four pectinate branches, two in HW; A3 simple in both wings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="36" pageNumber="37" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="36.[151,1437,433,854]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,757,782]" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">Comments.</emphasis>
The venation of this fossil genus is relatively typical for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1815" box="[1040,1161,757,782]" class="Insecta" family="Osmylidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Osmylinae">Osmylinae</taxonomicName>
and we agree with its placement in this subfamily by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lambkin" box="[509,693,793,818]" firstAuthor="Lambkin" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" pagination="295 - 300" refId="ref50097" refString="Lambkin, K. J. (1987) A re-examination of Euporismites balli Tillyard from the Palaeocene of Queensland (Neuroptera: Osmylidae: Kempyninae). Neuroptera International, 4, 295 - 300." type="journal article" year="1987">Lambkin (1987)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Wang" box="[749,976,793,818]" firstAuthor="Wang" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" pagination="865 - 869" refId="ref54921" refString="Wang, Y., Liu, Z., Ren, D. &amp; Shih, C (2011 a) New Middle Jurassic kempynin osmylid lacewings from China. Acta Palaeontologica Polonica, 56, 865 - 869. https: // doi. org / 10.4202 / app. 2010.0050" type="journal article" year="2011 a">
Wang 
<emphasis box="[822,879,793,818]" italics="true" pageId="36" pageNumber="37">et al.</emphasis>
(2011a)
</bibRefCitation>
, although considering the wing venation similarity, 
<bibRefCitation author="Carpenter" box="[270,462,830,854]" firstAuthor="Carpenter" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" pagination="753 - 760" refId="ref47880" refString="Carpenter, F. M. (1943) Osmylidae of the Florissant shales, Colorado (Insecta-Neuroptera). American Journal of Science, 241, 753 - 760. https: // doi. org / 10.2475 / ajs. 241.12.753" type="journal article" year="1943">Carpenter (1943)</bibRefCitation>
unsurprisingly regarded it as belonging to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carpenter" authorityYear="1943" box="[944,1091,829,854]" class="Insecta" family="Osmylidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="36" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Kempyninae">Kempyninae</taxonomicName>
. Only the wings are known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
